WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.360
Hello, everyone.

00:00:08.360 --> 00:00:09.680
Thanks for being here today.

00:00:09.680 --> 00:00:14.600
My name is Millie Sense, and I will be talking about a challenge that I created for myself

00:00:14.600 --> 00:00:20.120
last year, which was to create a website and a blog once a month for an entire year.

00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:24.320
So I'll be going over what I learned about myself and a lot of things just like in the

00:00:24.320 --> 00:00:25.320
process.

00:00:25.760 --> 00:00:31.240
Before I get there, I want to bring you back to a point earlier in this year where a group

00:00:31.240 --> 00:00:36.160
of my friends, we all went to Puerto Rico for a bachelor party, and one of the activities

00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:37.959
was to go on a hike.

00:00:37.959 --> 00:00:43.040
It was not like any hike that I've been on before, where there were clear trails to walk

00:00:43.040 --> 00:00:44.040
on.

00:00:44.040 --> 00:00:51.540
We were climbing over rocks, crossing streams and rivers, and it was a lot, but nevertheless,

00:00:51.540 --> 00:00:57.580
we persisted with our guide who brought us to this beautiful waterfall, the most gorgeous

00:00:57.580 --> 00:00:58.580
thing I've ever seen.

00:00:58.580 --> 00:01:03.259
At some point, he says, oh, well, you could get closer to that waterfall.

00:01:03.259 --> 00:01:08.220
You just got to kind of climb a cliff, and there will be a pool area, you could swim

00:01:08.220 --> 00:01:10.220
and be under the waterfall.

00:01:10.220 --> 00:01:14.860
So at first, I was just like, nah, I'm not going to do that.

00:01:14.860 --> 00:01:16.339
That's a lot.

00:01:16.339 --> 00:01:17.339
That's scary.

00:01:17.339 --> 00:01:18.339
I don't want to do that.

00:01:18.339 --> 00:01:24.739
So watching my friends start climbing, I was like, okay, I guess I could do that, too.

00:01:24.739 --> 00:01:32.139
And to my own surprise, I actually did climb, and I got up there.

00:01:32.139 --> 00:01:37.620
I got up at this beautiful pool area, and it was a good example of that I could do hard

00:01:37.620 --> 00:01:40.300
things, too, if I just go ahead and do it.

00:01:40.300 --> 00:01:44.959
So I guess you're wondering, okay, waterfall, blogs, what is this connection?

00:01:45.760 --> 00:01:48.599
These two things were my own stretch points.

00:01:48.599 --> 00:01:53.239
There were times in which I decided to go ahead and do something, even though I didn't

00:01:53.239 --> 00:01:55.919
really think it was possible.

00:01:55.919 --> 00:02:00.000
So before blogging, I was in the education space.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:06.239
I worked at the City University of New York, and at IBM, I was doing education research

00:02:06.239 --> 00:02:08.399
and program evaluation.

00:02:08.399 --> 00:02:11.240
And now I'm currently a senior data analyst at Thinks.

00:02:11.240 --> 00:02:16.279
I'm moving to the analytics engineering space, for the most part.

00:02:16.279 --> 00:02:21.039
And towards the end of my time in education, I became a very big fan of the open source

00:02:21.039 --> 00:02:22.639
community.

00:02:22.639 --> 00:02:26.240
And now I feel like I can say I'm an R community contributor.

00:02:26.240 --> 00:02:33.240
Like, I have a blog now, and I am presenting to you all at the conference.

00:02:33.240 --> 00:02:35.759
This is crazy.

00:02:36.440 --> 00:02:41.440
But I didn't really know about this whole community until I got to attend the conference

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:43.240
in 2020.

00:02:43.240 --> 00:02:49.199
I was introduced to R at the City University of New York, because we spent some time transitioning

00:02:49.199 --> 00:02:56.520
our projects from Stata to R. So I learned just enough to do my job well, but I didn't

00:02:56.520 --> 00:03:00.679
know that there were so many other things that you could do until I was able to come

00:03:00.679 --> 00:03:02.800
to this conference.

00:03:02.800 --> 00:03:06.320
And just like how I feel like I would say that you all are experiencing this week of

00:03:06.320 --> 00:03:13.800
like really beautiful talks that are informative and inspiring about how we are all using the

00:03:13.800 --> 00:03:18.080
same tools in very different ways, I had that experience, too, in 2020.

00:03:18.080 --> 00:03:23.240
I got introduced to the cross between data and art and education.

00:03:23.240 --> 00:03:29.919
I got to learn more about how to not repeat yourself in reports and be more efficient.

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:33.880
And also learning all the millions of ways that you can use R Markdown that I had no

00:03:33.880 --> 00:03:36.080
idea you could do before.

00:03:36.080 --> 00:03:41.360
So at this point in my journey, I would say I was heavily into the observer role.

00:03:41.360 --> 00:03:46.119
I was happily taking in all of this information and really excited about it.

00:03:46.119 --> 00:03:49.119
At the same time, I really wanted to be a contributor.

00:03:49.119 --> 00:03:53.520
I wanted to be like the cool big kids that were like doing all the cool stuff.

00:03:53.520 --> 00:03:57.600
Like I wanted to be a part of it, and I felt really inspired.

00:03:57.720 --> 00:04:00.800
But there were so many options.

00:04:00.800 --> 00:04:04.960
I didn't know where to start, what to do, how to go about it.

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:10.839
So similar to my panic at this waterfall at the cliff, I kind of took a step back and

00:04:10.839 --> 00:04:14.240
was just like, no, I'm not going to do that.

00:04:14.240 --> 00:04:18.200
But an idea never really dies, at least in my opinion.

00:04:18.200 --> 00:04:24.079
So after the conference, you know, we go through a global pandemic, and I changed jobs and

00:04:24.079 --> 00:04:25.679
changed sectors.

00:04:25.679 --> 00:04:30.880
I started doing lots of, like, webinars and doing some of my own professional development

00:04:30.880 --> 00:04:35.519
online and attending meetups, a lot of virtual meetups online.

00:04:35.519 --> 00:04:42.040
And the idea and the thought of building this website just kind of kept popping up.

00:04:42.040 --> 00:04:47.040
And so at some point, I was like, all right, I guess I'll just do it.

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:52.040
Because the hardest part of anything, I think, is really just to start.

00:04:52.040 --> 00:04:54.600
So with all things are really big.

00:04:54.600 --> 00:04:57.480
I like to catch them in structure as much as I can.

00:04:57.480 --> 00:05:02.119
So I created this challenge for myself where I was going to, you know, just create and

00:05:02.119 --> 00:05:03.119
publish a website.

00:05:03.119 --> 00:05:09.079
I was going to write a blog post once a month for an entire year.

00:05:09.079 --> 00:05:15.880
And I chose this format because it was long enough for me to be able to jump in and have

00:05:15.880 --> 00:05:21.760
time to learn and try new things, but also short enough so that it's not, like, overwhelming.

00:05:21.760 --> 00:05:26.279
And it was just 12 blog posts that felt achievable.

00:05:26.279 --> 00:05:31.279
And then lastly, I wanted to make sure that I shared that blog publicly on LinkedIn and

00:05:31.279 --> 00:05:35.519
Twitter because I also wanted this to be an opportunity for me to talk about myself more

00:05:35.519 --> 00:05:37.279
and put myself out there.

00:05:37.279 --> 00:05:40.760
Because this is also, like, my first time kind of just, like, putting myself out there

00:05:40.760 --> 00:05:41.760
on the Internet.

00:05:41.760 --> 00:05:42.920
Because I didn't really have to before.

00:05:42.920 --> 00:05:46.760
But now that I've, like, switched sectors, it's kind of hard to talk about what it is

00:05:46.760 --> 00:05:50.799
that my expertise is without having a platform.

00:05:50.839 --> 00:05:54.600
So that's the way I went about this challenge.

00:05:54.600 --> 00:05:58.640
So thinking about the side effects of all of this, I think there were a lot of things

00:05:58.640 --> 00:06:00.760
that I learned and experienced.

00:06:00.760 --> 00:06:06.859
But the ones that I'm going to focus on today is related more to, like, professional development.

00:06:06.859 --> 00:06:12.640
So three things that I learned was how to build my brand.

00:06:12.640 --> 00:06:15.760
Figure out my niche in this big data space.

00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:20.040
And how to build and maintain this website.

00:06:20.040 --> 00:06:25.799
So when it came to my brand, or just, like, putting the website together and all, I was,

00:06:25.799 --> 00:06:29.480
like, okay, well, how am I going to introduce myself here?

00:06:29.480 --> 00:06:34.200
Like, what is Millie?

00:06:34.200 --> 00:06:39.920
So I had, like, a guiding question for myself, like, what do I want to be known for?

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:43.600
And I broke that down to, like, what is it that I do?

00:06:43.600 --> 00:06:44.760
Who am I?

00:06:44.760 --> 00:06:48.160
And who would I like to become, like, as a professional?

00:06:48.200 --> 00:06:51.640
And these were the questions that I was, like, asking myself and the answers that I would

00:06:51.640 --> 00:06:58.359
use in order to, like, build that, like, home, like, land page and bio.

00:06:58.359 --> 00:07:06.200
So I knew that I wanted to showcase my expertise in education and higher education especially.

00:07:06.200 --> 00:07:08.239
But I also wanted to show that I'm a multifaceted human.

00:07:08.239 --> 00:07:11.000
I like a lot of things.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:14.239
And I also wanted to showcase that I do care about societal issues.

00:07:14.239 --> 00:07:17.480
I want all of these things to kind of be incorporated all in one.

00:07:17.480 --> 00:07:23.279
So when it came to my home page, I basically took three sentences for those three questions

00:07:23.279 --> 00:07:25.559
and just, like, wrote an answer to each one.

00:07:25.559 --> 00:07:30.239
And that became kind of, like, my elevator pitch for my site.

00:07:30.239 --> 00:07:36.359
And then into, like, the about me section, same concept, but now I just have that broken

00:07:36.359 --> 00:07:38.920
out bigger in little paragraphs.

00:07:38.920 --> 00:07:43.679
So you get to know who I am and what I care about, details on what I do professionally,

00:07:43.679 --> 00:07:45.000
and a little bit about me personally.

00:07:45.480 --> 00:07:46.720
I like watching turtles sunbathe.

00:07:46.720 --> 00:07:51.359
It's one of my favorite things.

00:07:51.359 --> 00:07:59.359
So after figuring out, okay, this is how I'm going to showcase myself on this site, now,

00:07:59.359 --> 00:08:02.519
how am I showing up once a month for a year?

00:08:02.519 --> 00:08:07.000
I didn't know really what it is that I wanted to, like, write about.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:11.880
So I decided to have this, like, guiding question to think through, well, how do I want people

00:08:11.880 --> 00:08:15.640
to experience me?

00:08:15.640 --> 00:08:22.119
So I did lots of I spent lots of time looking at different websites from all over across

00:08:22.119 --> 00:08:23.320
the community.

00:08:23.320 --> 00:08:28.519
So there were students that were showcasing what they were learning in classes and a little

00:08:28.519 --> 00:08:33.719
bit of, like, small projects on their site, to professors showing their whole curriculum

00:08:33.719 --> 00:08:39.719
portfolio online, or even folks in the community giving, like, really detailed guided tutorials

00:08:39.719 --> 00:08:44.400
on how to do anything that you can think of or any problem that you're having.

00:08:44.400 --> 00:08:48.880
And with looking at all of that inspiration, I also wanted to think about what my strengths

00:08:48.880 --> 00:08:50.880
are and what I could, like, showcase.

00:08:50.880 --> 00:08:55.400
But also what I wanted to learn, because this whole thing was a learning experience for

00:08:55.400 --> 00:08:56.520
me.

00:08:56.520 --> 00:09:02.039
So with that, I got these, like, kind of, like, keywords of how it is that I want to

00:09:02.039 --> 00:09:03.320
show up.

00:09:03.320 --> 00:09:06.400
And so I knew that I want information to be in small bites.

00:09:06.400 --> 00:09:09.200
I want it to be, like, short and sweet.

00:09:09.200 --> 00:09:11.599
People can, like, read it within five minutes or so.

00:09:11.599 --> 00:09:16.320
It was really important for me to have it be friendly and approachable.

00:09:16.320 --> 00:09:21.880
And I also wanted to showcase, like, my big picture thinking.

00:09:21.880 --> 00:09:27.520
And so that's where I landed on this title for my blog, called deviations outside of

00:09:27.520 --> 00:09:28.520
the norm.

00:09:28.520 --> 00:09:32.919
Because, you know, who doesn't like a cute play on words with stats?

00:09:32.919 --> 00:09:37.320
And I wanted to showcase it that way to say, like, this will be a data blog of some sort,

00:09:37.320 --> 00:09:41.559
but it might not be like the ones that you've come across, because I'm going to capture

00:09:41.559 --> 00:09:43.000
it in a lot of different things.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:46.359
And I also feel like I'm a little bit of a deviation outside of the norm.

00:09:46.359 --> 00:09:49.440
But, you know, neither here nor there.

00:09:49.440 --> 00:09:53.760
So my opening blogs, I started off with something I felt really confident about and I could

00:09:53.760 --> 00:09:55.960
talk about for hours.

00:09:55.960 --> 00:09:58.000
And it is logic models.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:03.320
Which I think is very important for anyone who's working in any sort of programming to

00:10:03.320 --> 00:10:07.320
have a logic model so that you know what it is that your outcomes are and how you're

00:10:07.320 --> 00:10:08.320
going to go about it.

00:10:08.320 --> 00:10:09.320
But, okay.

00:10:09.320 --> 00:10:10.320
That's aside.

00:10:10.320 --> 00:10:12.599
So I did that.

00:10:12.599 --> 00:10:17.799
And then for my second post, I did do, like, a little tutorial, but I couched it in, like,

00:10:17.799 --> 00:10:19.880
a bigger story and a bigger lesson.

00:10:19.880 --> 00:10:23.799
So it was more than just, you know, how to make a Gantt chart.

00:10:24.159 --> 00:10:32.760
And as time progressed, I, like, really, like, gave some time into showing up with my art.

00:10:32.760 --> 00:10:37.359
Because I also thought this would be, like, a cool opportunity for me to just dig a little

00:10:37.359 --> 00:10:38.359
bit more.

00:10:38.359 --> 00:10:46.200
Because in that 2020 conference, I got introduced to Allison Horst, who I love her art so much.

00:10:46.200 --> 00:10:51.159
And she was doing all the things that I, like, envisioned or, like, wanted to do for myself.

00:10:51.159 --> 00:10:57.039
So this was, like, my way to, like, challenge myself to also bring in art into my cute little

00:10:57.039 --> 00:10:58.039
data space.

00:10:58.039 --> 00:10:59.039
Thank you.

00:10:59.039 --> 00:11:08.719
So lastly, with building and maintaining a website.

00:11:08.719 --> 00:11:12.239
So definitely big thanks to Allison Hill.

00:11:12.239 --> 00:11:17.719
She spent some time with me as we crossed paths in IBM for a second to just, like, sit

00:11:17.719 --> 00:11:23.880
down and help me walk through connecting my project through GitHub and connecting it

00:11:23.880 --> 00:11:25.320
to Netlify.

00:11:25.320 --> 00:11:31.640
And then I had the fun part of figuring out everything else.

00:11:31.640 --> 00:11:37.719
And that meant a lot of, like, not understanding how to do things, lots of breaking things.

00:11:37.719 --> 00:11:47.559
Deep appreciation and also pain with Git.

00:11:47.559 --> 00:11:51.080
This was also my first opportunity to really dig into Git as well.

00:11:51.080 --> 00:11:54.039
In my previous jobs, I haven't had to use it.

00:11:54.039 --> 00:11:55.039
So yeah.

00:11:55.039 --> 00:11:57.719
I mean, I'm still struggling.

00:11:57.719 --> 00:12:02.320
But it at least is helpful while you have a project that you care about to couch it

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:03.320
in that.

00:12:03.320 --> 00:12:07.840
So I got introduced to other packages as well.

00:12:07.840 --> 00:12:11.559
As I was, like, trying to learn things and also write blog posts.

00:12:11.559 --> 00:12:15.599
So this bigger project became smaller projects within smaller projects.

00:12:15.599 --> 00:12:19.799
And just kind of built up on all these things that I got to learn that I feel like will

00:12:19.799 --> 00:12:23.880
be transferable wherever it is that I go.

00:12:23.880 --> 00:12:32.719
So when it comes to resources for making websites, blogs, for a site like mine that uses Hugo,

00:12:32.719 --> 00:12:35.840
Allison Hill has really great posts on this.

00:12:35.840 --> 00:12:39.460
She, like, details exactly what it is that you need to do.

00:12:39.460 --> 00:12:44.239
But if you are looking to do something a little bit more simpler, there is Distill and Andreas

00:12:44.239 --> 00:12:49.359
Handel and Thomas Malk has some sites that have a guided tutorial.

00:12:49.359 --> 00:12:52.640
But better yet, of course, try Cordo.

00:12:52.640 --> 00:12:58.039
And I highly recommend Isabella Velasquez's site, because she has a whole site that is

00:12:58.039 --> 00:13:03.479
about helping you get to the point of having Cordo be the base for your own website and

00:13:03.479 --> 00:13:05.700
blog.

00:13:05.700 --> 00:13:11.159
So thinking about this journey of going from observer to contributor, I chose a website

00:13:11.280 --> 00:13:16.119
for my own specific reasons, for my own professional development, and wanted to pivot out of the

00:13:16.119 --> 00:13:17.119
education space.

00:13:17.119 --> 00:13:20.400
But I think there are so many ways that anyone can contribute.

00:13:20.400 --> 00:13:24.440
And these are just a small few out of the many ways in which you could do it.

00:13:24.440 --> 00:13:31.280
But generative art, doing lunch and learns at work, package development, or doing virtual

00:13:31.280 --> 00:13:38.760
or in-person meetups are all the ways and more to really move from that transition of

00:13:38.760 --> 00:13:43.440
being an observer and start going into the contributor realm.

00:13:43.440 --> 00:13:49.039
So I leave you with this question of, like, what is your waterfall?

00:13:49.039 --> 00:13:51.719
What is that stretch point that you have for yourself?

00:13:51.719 --> 00:13:58.159
What have you been thinking about doing for a while for yourself and the community?

00:13:58.159 --> 00:14:00.640
And really dig into that thought.

00:14:00.640 --> 00:14:05.080
Because one of the things I think that I have learned in this whole experience of building

00:14:05.080 --> 00:14:12.760
this website is that at any point in my art journey, I could have inputted my voice in

00:14:12.760 --> 00:14:13.760
there.

00:14:13.760 --> 00:14:14.760
And it would have been of value.

00:14:14.760 --> 00:14:17.520
And someone else would have also wanted to hear it.

00:14:17.520 --> 00:14:22.000
So take this as your sign to get creative and do that thing that you've been thinking

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:23.640
about for a long time.

00:14:23.640 --> 00:14:27.159
Because there is someone else that needs to hear your voice, too.

00:14:27.159 --> 00:14:28.159
Yeah.

00:14:28.159 --> 00:14:29.159
Thanks.

00:14:29.159 --> 00:14:38.960
All right.

00:14:38.960 --> 00:14:39.960
Thank you, Millie.

00:14:39.960 --> 00:14:41.880
So a couple of questions from the audience.

00:14:41.880 --> 00:14:47.200
Number one, what was the turning point for you that made you just start the process to

00:14:47.200 --> 00:14:48.440
finally create your website?

00:14:48.440 --> 00:14:52.880
Any significant motivation or single event that fueled it?

00:14:52.880 --> 00:14:53.880
It was...

00:14:53.880 --> 00:14:54.880
Well, I think...

00:14:54.880 --> 00:14:55.880
Yeah.

00:14:55.880 --> 00:14:59.119
I think Allison Hill also telling me that it would be helpful.

00:14:59.119 --> 00:15:03.119
Because she was talking about how she was in the process of trying to hire some data

00:15:03.119 --> 00:15:04.520
scientists.

00:15:04.520 --> 00:15:08.159
And she said, like, it just makes a difference for someone to just have, like, an online

00:15:08.159 --> 00:15:10.340
platform for people to browse through.

00:15:10.340 --> 00:15:12.440
And after hearing it so many times.

00:15:12.440 --> 00:15:15.640
And then when your idol, you know, really comes up and she's like, yeah, you should

00:15:15.640 --> 00:15:16.640
do it.

00:15:16.640 --> 00:15:18.440
And it's like, well, I guess I'll have to do it then.

00:15:18.440 --> 00:15:19.440
Like, geez.

00:15:19.440 --> 00:15:21.960
So that was the moment for me.

00:15:22.039 --> 00:15:24.919
Well, thank you, Allison Hill.

00:15:24.919 --> 00:15:25.919
Question number two.

00:15:25.919 --> 00:15:31.960
How do you maintain a blog and personal morale, even if nobody seems to read your posts?

00:15:31.960 --> 00:15:34.280
This is one of my biggest anxieties.

00:15:34.280 --> 00:15:35.679
Oh.

00:15:35.679 --> 00:15:41.880
So for me, I basically pretended like I was in my own part of the internet where no one

00:15:41.880 --> 00:15:44.000
read it.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:45.400
And I was okay with that.

00:15:45.400 --> 00:15:49.159
Because, like, I'm learning something and I'm putting posts out there.

00:15:49.159 --> 00:15:51.280
So I just really couched it.

00:15:51.280 --> 00:15:54.239
I'm like, this is something that I'm doing for me.

00:15:54.239 --> 00:15:58.080
And then it was a happy bonus when folks would be like, oh, my gosh, I really love this post.

00:15:58.080 --> 00:16:04.880
Or a friend of mine told me that he was literally sending posts to his supervisee for reference.

00:16:04.880 --> 00:16:06.880
Oh, yeah, Millie has a thing.

00:16:06.880 --> 00:16:08.119
You should go ahead and do that.

00:16:08.119 --> 00:16:10.239
And I'm just like, why are you doing this?

00:16:10.239 --> 00:16:12.039
I was like, oh, you really like this.

00:16:12.039 --> 00:16:15.760
People would be, like, looking forward to the next post.

00:16:15.760 --> 00:16:18.640
So people are out here on the internet looking at the site.

00:16:18.640 --> 00:16:19.640
That's crazy.

00:16:19.640 --> 00:16:21.880
But, yeah, no, I did it for me.

00:16:21.880 --> 00:16:23.400
And I think that helped with my anxiety.

00:16:23.400 --> 00:16:30.880
Because otherwise, if I put my value into how many views there are, and I don't check

00:16:30.880 --> 00:16:34.239
how many people get into the site or anything like that, then it would feel a little bit

00:16:34.239 --> 00:16:35.239
different for me.

00:16:35.239 --> 00:16:36.599
And I would have a different kind of anxiety.

00:16:36.599 --> 00:16:39.000
But when you do it for yourself, I feel like it should be okay.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:40.000
Yeah.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:41.000
Okay.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:42.000
Fantastic.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:43.000
Let's thank Millie again.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:44.000
Thank you.

